review.reviewBody: I purchased a few of the previous version and they were excellent quality YUPOONG brand hats with a nice patch style logo. The new version is inferior in my opinion, but costs the same. MH made “recycled materials” the priority over quality, and it shows compared to the previous version. The new version is made by NetPlus, which I’ve never heard of for hats, but because they make the brim out of recycled materials, they got the nod. The hat just feels cheap and doesn’t look as good, and the logo patch is just a thin piece of nylon that (on mine) is slightly crooked. The crown is shallower so it sits closer to your head than the previous trucker, and the bill is a little too big for the hat. I’ve been a MH fan boy for over 20 years, but they skimped on this hat in the name of recycled materials. I’m all for sustainability, but we shouldn’t push so hard to market “recycled” if the end result is sub par.

review.reviewBody:
I have worn these shorts for about 7 months. The amount of pilling on loose threads on these shorts is surprising. I had higher expectations. I have worn the shorts primarily as casual wear, with some hiking and climbing as well. Particularly given that they haven't seen much abrasion I am very disappointed with the excessive wear. 

Very comfortable shorts, but I cannot recommend and will not buy again.

The photo provides a representation of what the shorts look like, though I think it looks worse in person.
review.name: Poor Durability

review.reviewBody: Very pleased with this. I get extra discount from here: coupon-bird.com
review.name: Great quality for the price

review.reviewBody:
I did a lot of research on these before buying.  The reviews were great.  I swallowed the blue pill and bought three pairs.  Wow, what a disappointment.

If tofu and tissue paper had a baby, this would be their offspring.  I've hardly worn these (wash on delicate, line dry) and they're already showing signs of wear on the legs.  There's also a lot of pilling.

Seriously, for this price, you should be getting a lot higher quality.  I've bought shorts from Goodwill for a couple bucks that were higher quality than these.

Bottom Line: I have no idea who's writing these reviews (Prana bloggers?), but these are the least durable shorts I've ever owned.  I'm actually afraid of hiking in them.

Please don't waste your money.  You've been warned.  Oh, and btw, the sizing is very inconsistant.  So, don't expect to get the sizing right the first (or possibly second) time.

Update: I talked to Prana corporate.  They said to contact Backcountry and ask for a refund.  I then contacted Backcountry and they indicated that since they're used and outside the 30-day return window, I'd have to contact Prana.  Prana said that they'd only provide a partial refund for the lowest sale price on record.  I asked for an exchange instead.  They said, "We don't do that."  So, I'd have to return them, receive a partial refund, then pay full price for something else on the Prana website.  No refund, no exchange.  Wow.  Prana is owned by Columbia.  I've been a loyal customer of Columbia for decades.  Unfortunately, more and more apparel companies are acting like this.  So, be warned.  This is how Prana treats their customers.  Profits over quality and customer loyalty.
review.name: Not Durable At All

review.reviewBody: The material is sturdy enough yet not too hot on those uber warm days. They feel indestructible but look very nice and not out of place in a classy setting. i should by more colorways of these!
review.name: These pants Rock

review.reviewBody: These things are great!  From the Zion stretch fabric to the fit, finish and style. I like them so much I got them in an assortment of colors.

review.reviewBody: love these shorts. more fitted than the zions i had for years. good for the trail, then straight to cocktails!
review.name: Great Shorts

review.reviewBody: Basically the best climbing shorts I've ever owned. Got the 11" inseam which is perfect, I don't want to be that dude with really short shorts at the gym. Great for lead or bouldering, high-stepping is not a problem with the flexible material. They seem durable. I like that there are no cargo pockets so getting a harness on/off is no problem. I started wearing them most days and will probably get more.
review.name: Perfect for climbing and everything else

review.reviewBody: These look like classic 5 pocket shorts, but are way more comfortable with the stretch fabric and gusseted crotch.  I have 3 pairs and wore these almost everyday this past spring and summer.

review.reviewBody: This is my favorite sealant. Cleans up easily, has yet to not seal a puncture, and is usually readily available at most bike shops if I need to grab a bottle to top up for some reason.
review.name: My favorite sealant

review.reviewBody: Stan's is fantastic!  I use the sealant in my MTB inner tubes, not tubeless.  I live in an area with "goat heads" I was getting flats on every ride, then I put Stan's in my 29ers x 2.35 (40-50 mL).  No flats since!  I add about 5-10 mL every 3 months.  After 18 months no flats still on the same inner tubes and I rarely add air to my wheels.  Great product if you are prone to getting thorn punctures.  When you consider the cost of a flat (lost trail time), patches, and inner tubes, Stan's ends up being pennies per mile and less frustration.  Definitely worth the cost of a 1 L bottle.
review.name: Great for MTB inner tubes!  No flats!

review.reviewBody: Used this on my gravel bike and haven't had a flat since. Update: 3/15/21 Still no flats!
review.name: No More Flats

review.reviewBody: I put 5 ounces of this sealant in each tube. The only way I can get a flat is with a sidewall tire failure. Only if this happens will the sealant not prevent a flat. That can happen at any time, especially if you ride into a deep pothole. Any failure of the tube and this sealant will plug it. It makes no sense to ride with any back up tubes as long as I have sealant in my tubes. The sealant lasts about 5-6 months and I replace my Continental 4 Season tires and tubes every 2500 miles. After 2500 miles the tires are more prone to fail, especially on the sidewall areas. What is amazing to me is all of these experienced cyclist who ride without any knowledge of sealant. Make sure to get removable valve cores and load up your tubes with sealant. I go on 75 mile rides with no back up gear, no saddle pack because I trust this product. I had one flat in the past 3 years and it was due to a sidewall tire failure. That's 30k + miles with one flat.
review.name: Terrific Product

review.reviewBody: My go-to sealant, works great.
review.name: Great stuff

review.reviewBody: Always have some of this on hand. Sealant dries out/gets nasty over time so, as a part of my monthly service, it's good to check the status of the sealant in my tires. Stan's, for me, is the only way to go.
review.name: Works great

review.reviewBody: Had my first flat ever since going tubeless and 2 sets of tires. My first time using Stans.
review.name: Not Sold On Stans
comment: Go back to tubes. I have heard many complaints from people going tubeless. I use this product in my tubes and it works great. Your problem is with tubeless tires, not the sealant.

Overall, they're incredibly comfortable snowshoes. 

However, the main issue I'd return them is that, on a 10-mile hike, at least one of the heel straps came undone every 0.5 miles on average (and at times, multiple times within 100 yards). I had to re-strap them many times, and this became frustrating. I'm looking into a binding system instead that'll prevent this from happening. Would NOT recommend for this reason.

review.reviewBody:
I've truly relished my time using these snowshoes. They've been put through their paces, conquering deep Montana powder as well as tackling late-season trails covered in hard-packed ice. One standout feature is the remarkable binding system, which, in my experience, surpasses any other binding I've encountered in terms of ease of use.

However, it's worth noting that when navigating icy and rocky terrain, these snowshoes excel in performance but come with one noticeable drawback – they're quite noisy. Sneaking up on anything becomes an impossible feat.

One minor inconvenience I've encountered is the necessity to always wear gaiters with these snowshoes. The metal edge, while providing excellent traction, can occasionally feel like a double-edged sword, as it has the potential to catch on the inside of your legs and, more often than not, on your clothing.

All in all, despite these minor quirks, my overall experience with these snowshoes has been exceptionally positive, and they have proven their worth in a variety of challenging conditions. Whether conquering deep powder or icy trails, these snowshoes are an outstanding choice.

review.reviewBody:
After three seasons using these snow shoes in Alaska I have been impressed at the quality, durability and function. I use these snow shoes for back country travel and hunting in untracked terrain, the add on tails can help depending on snow conditions. The step bars are a great help to save foot stress when climbing steeper slopes. The group of five I travel with all have the same snow shoes and we have only had one breakage of a heel strap in the last three years. When traveling in untracked snow i appreciate the way the snow shoes keep the snow from pushing out the and aid in compaction of the snow under foot to minimize postholing.

I will note that the comments about the teeth damaging clothing can occur if the user is not used to keeping their feet apart when snow shoeing. I do not like these snow shoes on packed/heavily used trails that are ice resembling concrete since the frames having the teeth on the outer edge like to flex and I worry about breakage, i would recommend a different style snow shoe or foot wear traction if your travel is on hard packed/ ice trails.

review.reviewBody:
This is the warmest coat I have ever purchased. EVER!!!! That being said, it is NOT form-fitting. I look like a giant blue marshmallow or Ralphie's brother from A Christmas Story... but alas, I am warm. :) 

I have taken it on mountain backpacking trips/winter adventures and I have been super comfy/at times really toasty in -20 degrees C and below. Of course I accompany it with a base layer, mid layer, and more depending on conditions. 

My favorite features of this coat: the hood has a brim which keeps it from sliding down over your eyes, it is a bit longer in the back which keeps your bum nice and warm when sitting down, it comes with a stuff sack so you can pack it down really small, and the hydrophobic down and Pertex Quantum material have kept me dry in unexpected snowstorms (which I love as I do not have to worry about quickly switching/adding layers)!! 

Before I purchased this coat, I was looking for a product that could keep me warm, minimize the amount of layers I was wearing, AND could handle moisture as Mother Nature can change her mind in a split second. The Rab Positron checked many of my boxes!! I have taken this coat backcountry snowboarding and cross-country skiing and I do not quite recommend it for those activities (but that is just my opinion)! When I was snowboarding, I was not able to be as mobile and flexible as I would like. Cross-country skiing was similar and I was WAY too hot, whew!!! Using it for backpacking, winter hikes/winter camping, mountaineering though - it is perfect!!

review.reviewBody: I purchased this backpack in November, but didn't use it until February of this year and have now used it a total of three times. I bought this pack primarily for road cycling. I thoroughly cleaned the pack according to manufacturer's instructions, which removed the odor, but it returned immediately after my next 20-mile ride.  Again, I gave it a thorough cleaning, sprayed with Lysol, and cleaned again, but it happened once again and I'm no longer willing to deal with this piece of crap. review.reviewBody:
Hyperlite mountain gear blatanly lies about their tents. 
I bought this junk tent in Jan . 30,2018 and from the get go I found it to be considerably less roomy than advertised. The photos on their website are photoshopped. The dysee
ma fabric is not the strongest of any backpack tent. The zipper separated from the tent fabric after only 2 years of use. This is in no way a 4 season tent! It lets in  the rain/snow  if you must exit/enter because of the pyramid design and is at best a flimsy 2-3 season tent!

review.reviewBody: Tried in with my ski touring boots and Mountaineering B2 boots and the gaiters just fall down. I'll try a different brand until OR adds the cam locks back or some other better system.  Too many bad reviews on the buckles busting for me to repy on them in the extreme alpine

review.reviewBody:
I've always been a fan of the OR Expedition Crocodiles Gaiters.  Wear them off trail in some pretty nasty conditions and they hold up well.

Ordered a new pair and sized up to accommodate my bulkier pac boots. When I went to fit the gaiter to my boots found one of the buckle prongs for the instep strap was installed backwards.  The prong does not lay flat like it's designed to. 

Maybe a minor inspection issue but sort of a PITA now to adjust the strap fit in the field with gloves.  The prong also sticks up rather than laying flat against the buckle making it more susceptible to damage on brush and rock.
review.name: Instep buckle installed backwards

review.reviewBody: Best gatorz money can buy I use them on every hike and never had snow or water get in my boots, not to mention amazing customer service. Highly recommend.
review.name: Best gaitorz out there

review.reviewBody: Best Gaiters we own, with the best warranty!!
review.name: Best Gaiters

review.reviewBody: Disclaimer: I haven't had a chance to use the gaiters, they just arrived a couple of days ago. This review is for people concerned about sizing. I plan to wear the gaiters (size L) with size 10 (US Men) low-profile, lightly-insulated mountaineering boots. Having tried them on, they fit the boot perfectly. On the other end, the top of the gaiters (wrapping around above my calves) could also be tightened significantly to fit comfortably/stably around my smaller-than-average legs. However, the size L gaiters would be far too large for "ordinary" size 10 shoes. I suspect this is where all of the reviews about the gaiters being too big come from.
review.name: Sizing seems just right

review.reviewBody: I love my Rosa sandals.  Usually I am wearing them without the straps but I do like that I have the option.  I snagged the Water Blue on sale and so glad I did.  I wear a 9-9.5 and the size 9 is perfect.  I love the fresh color.  Thanks Astral for another great pair of shoes in my wardrobe!
review.name: Rosa in Water Blue

review.reviewBody: I bought the Rosa over five years ago, and it's still going strong! I wear it all summer, for everything from beach days to hiking, always with the straps. The straps to wear out and I have to email the company to ask for replacements, but the sandals are extremely well made!
review.name: Best sandal for everything

review.reviewBody: Rosas are definitely the best flip flop I've ever owned. Very comfortable and grippy. The super strap is a must, I never take it off -- super useful in tricky situations and adds a little flare when not in use.
review.name: LOVE 'EM!

review.reviewBody: The strap is versatile, you can wear it as a flip, or move the strap around your heal when  the trail gets serious, for a more secure fit.  The foot bed is so comfortable, and the sandal is light.  Fits true to size.
review.name: Versatile & comfortable

review.reviewBody: So I've had these sandals for almost 5 years now (yes, same original pr)!!! They've been great and are still going strong, one back strap is beginning to see a little wear & won't stay super tight but still works great. I absolutely hate the weight and feel of Chacos, but was needing something in that category to wear on a trip to Disney. Wanted to be comfortable, knowing my feet would be getting wet whether it was on a ride or rain, and didn't want to slop around in wet tennis shoes. Went to my local river outfitters (we live in between 2 whitewater rivers) and confessed to the owner while standing under the huge Chaco sign that I hate them. He winked & said, personally I do too,lol, let me show you what I wear instead. And he talked me in to a pr of Astral Rosa's. Since then I've talked several friends in to them! Was a great deal for me because after the trip to Disney I was still able to wear them on the river, camping or just quick trips to town because they're so cute AND comfortable. I've even taken them to the beach with me!
review.name: Great!

review.reviewBody: These sandles are so versatile, light weight and goes well with casual and dressy attire. I love them so much I have them in every color.
review.name: Quality and customer service bar none

review.reviewBody: I would recommend this to everyone that spends time outdoors! Water and sand.
review.name: Best purchase of the year

review.reviewBody: These are my favorite sandals! I've owned them for about a year and they are extremely versatile and very comfortable while hiking and climbing on slippery river rocks. I dropped one star only because the ankle strap has already worn out on mine and won't tighten and has tears.
review.name: Great flip flops

review.reviewBody: These shoes rubbed 4 blisters on my feet; BOTH sides of each foot where the straps come through.
review.name: Nice looking BUT torture on your feet

review.reviewBody: Recently bought these sandals in the light gray and so far love them. I normally wear 9-9 1/2 in most shoes and the 9 in these fit me perfectly. They are lightweight, cushy comfortable and stay on my feet, which is a bonus because I have such narrow feet. I plan to take them on travel because I can use them paddle boarding, as well as around the hotel/hostel (especially when staying someplace with shared baths/showers) or around wet areas in general. Plus they are so cute! Probably will get another pair, maybe eventually in all the colors.
review.name: Great travel sandals

review.itemreviewed: Stinson ATR 7 Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: I purchased these upon a recommendation from my Doctor, who claimed HOKA trail running shoes were the best for over pronation and Plantar Fasciitis. He was right! These shoes have the best support of the many I've tried. (These are better than Brooks-Beast.) However, my Dr was also right when he mentioned their limited life span. I am several weeks into owner ship with a little under 40 walking miles (pavement and sidewalk/concrete) and the bottom soles towards the front-center show significant wear. Probably the quickest wearing sneaker I'ver ever purchased. While I understand the premium price and short lifespan for what is arguably the best-in-class supportive shoe, I'd still like to see improvements made to increase durability without compromising comfort/support.
review.name: Best Support for Plantar fasciitis, but wears out quickly.

The only thing that could top it would be a lightweight goretex version.

They felt fairly lightweight and stretchy, so I wasn't sure how warm they'd be on our wonderful Michigan chairlift rides and 20 second runs. I'll say they've held up very well, kept me warm with only a baselayer underneath, and have been more durable than I expected skiing trees. One thing to note is they run long. I'm 6'1 230lbs and 38x32 or 34...these legs are super long! They're fine with ski boots on but I included a photo comparing them to my old TNF ski pants as well.

review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I'm not a skier/snowboarder, bought these for a winter hiking in the Rocky Mountains and for the Sierra. 
They are lightly insulated, enough to be warm but not bulky.  The material is soft, slightly flexible, not hard and "crispy".  I like that they are quiet and easy to move around in.  

They are fairly slim-fitting, but there is an adjustable waistband. 

The only ding is the fact that Marmot doesn't make these with multiple inseam lengths: I wear a "short" inseam so I had them tailored.
review.name: Warm, flexible, soft, comfortable

review.reviewBody: This sleeping pad is amazing. As a fanatic for winter camping and this sleeping bad is more comfortable and quieter than competitors on the market. Highly recommend for those of you who plan on camping in the mountains.
review.name: Exemplary!

review.reviewBody: I slept on this pad for a week during a canoe trip this summer. It was warm, comfortable, and quiet. I loved how easy it was to deflate each morning.
review.name: Comfortable and quiet

review.reviewBody: This might be my favourite pad from NEMO. The insulation isn't just good for winter, but year-round. It's easy to inflate using the supplied NEMO inflation bag, and rolls-up and packs down to the size of a water bottle. Highly recommended for anyone who only wants one mat in their quiver, or for people who sleep cool.
review.name: Warm, quick to inflate, comfortable night's sleep

review.reviewBody: The Tensor EC is a great balance of warmth + comfort in a lightweight, packable size. I have used the "regular wide" version in combination with a foam Nemo Switchback for ski expeditions in Patagonia, British Columbia, and Iceland. When skiing with a partner, we can easily fit two pads in a Nemo Chogori 2p and provide a comfortable buffer from the snow on the tent floor. I particularly appreciate how easy it is to roll up the pad to a similar size it originally shipped in--it actually fits quite easily in the bag it came in, which feels like a rarity among most inflatable pads. Would recommend this to anyone winter camping / climbing / skiing!
review.name: Best Winter Camping Inflatable Pad

review.reviewBody:
I bought this three months ago. Unbelievable to compare the size, weight and the performance.  It is less noisy while using it, compare to other brands. Long and wide size makes it comfy for 6.3ft tall person.
Only feedback is problem with Vortex pump Sack! may be I don't know how to use it. Blowing in to it did not work well when I am cold, or after a long hiking days. Other than this, it is a amazing product.
review.name: It's expensive..but worth of it.

review.reviewBody: Great sleeping pad! Super comfortable, packs small, and provides a great night's sleep regardless of the temperatures!
review.name: Light, small and comfortable!

review.reviewBody:
Very happy I grabbed one of these going into last winter. I had been doubling up, inflatable + closed cell pad, to get through my winter camping and snow cave trips. I was getting by, but the bulk of carrying it all in was frustrating.
This pad was certainly not cheap but I would argue it paid for itself after one winter. Once it is rolled up with the inflator bag in the stuff sack, or just wrapped up with the nice little strap they included, it is barely larger or heavier than my lightweight summer pad. The construction and durability seem really solid. I slept a few nights with it directly on the snow and stayed warm and comfy all night. It has me starting to think I could go with a lighter sleeping bag and still be ok. 
The Vortex inflator bag is a little weird in that you have to blow into it to get it to inflate. However, it’s incredibly lightweight and quite efficient; 3 full bags will inflate the whole pad. The valve on the pad is fine, but I wish there was a better way to fine tune the inflation. If you want to bleed off a tiny amount of air you have to pop the valve wide open and very quickly close it back. Not a deal breaker by any means. 
Overall, great product, definitely lives up to its R-value. Would definitely recommend (and already have).
review.name: Must-have winter pad

review.reviewBody: I am very happy with this purchase. It’s a high quality sleeping pad and easy to blow up!
review.name: Great product!

review.reviewBody:
It's an investment, but you will not regret. It makes a big difference in comfort and weight. If you spend any significant time camping outdoors go get one. 
It works in all temperature ranges, it's not noisy as some people seem to say. The pouch is tight, but far from impossible if you roll it properly. It inflates very quick. Definitely get the wide version unless you're skinny and don't move at all. 
After 20+ years working and traveling outdoors, I was totally sold on this pad after 1 night. Looking forward to putting it to the test and enjoying good sleeps more often.
review.name: Makes a difference

review.reviewBody: Lightweight, extremely comfortable, and had me sweating in a snowstorm. It’s nice to know there’s a pad that I can trust in any Colorado conditions, and it weighs less than my tensor alpine wide long. Total win
review.name: The perfect pad for me

review.reviewBody:
This is a large tent, large enough for three cots, that you can stand up in, it has two different entranceways, one of them has a half screen window, which is a nice feature, If you do not use that as a doorway that it simply is another window to allow for cross ventilation. The rain fly does not come off the tent, though it can be peeled back for the last 1/6 of the 10th space which again is helpful for ventilation, but not as great as being able to have the fly completely removable. The screened investable is a decent size, however, it does not zip at the bottom, so it is certainly not going to keep bugs out, the doorway that would be the main entranceway into the tent does not have a zipper screen, and this is the biggest flaw of all. For this price point, the main entranceway should have a screen door. 

Camped with this tent during a low-grade hurricane/tropical storm in North Carolina, and it was fine.

review.reviewBody:
Have been running Ultegra 11-32 cassettes for some time. I'll generally get a random knockoff low gear in the 34t or 36 range to customize the cassette. While this works, it generally degrades shifting due to having to remove one of the lower gears. Decided to give Roadlink DM a test and was pretty happy with the results. 

Using 11 speed Ultegra Di2 and a Shimano XT 11-40 cassette performance has been better than the custom cassette and arguably as good as a standard 11-32. After a few hundred miles I have experienced no shifting issues and noise is as quiet or better than stock.

review.reviewBody: I've used these for an entire fall/winter/spring for commuting, and they are hardly warm at all. I found my fingers to be uncomfortably cold at anything below about 45F (7C), and they are unusable below 35F (2C). The rest of the hand is usually fine, but the fingers are downright miserable. Felt like I was getting frostbite.
review.name: Not nearly as warm as advertised

review.reviewBody:
There's very little to like about these gloves. They look nice sitting on a shelf. They work with a touchscreen. They will probably last a while. That's about it.

On the hand, here's all that I found wrong --
- Internal seam between leather palm and other fabrics is very stiff & scratchy. The first time I slid them on, I actually took them off immediately thinking I had left some packing material in there. Nope. Just the terribly large and poky seam.
- There is no give/stretch to the leather. On a palm, that's ok. Across the back of the knuckles? Not so much. They feel really tight there when you grip a handlebar
- There is no pre-curvature to this glove. And given how it is constructed, this makes the glove unusable with any modicum of comfort when you actually use them, you know, on a bike!
- They feel much cooler on the bike given the weight in hand. I wore them on a mid to high 40s ride and found my hands cold.

In general, this is a hard pass. Not sure I can return them, but I sure will try.
review.name: Look nice, feel awful on the hand

review.reviewBody: They seem like a good, quality glove.  They are windproof but with no insulation.  I found them to be really uncomfortable on a long ride.  After a couple hours, the fabric across the knuckles really started to be irritating.  They are not as comfortable as the Gore Windstopper gloves they replace.
review.name: They're OK.

review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This bag is great for anyone doing backpacking and traveling and camping.
This is a very large bag that will hold so much stuff. It will hold everything you need to go on a trip.
I like how light it is but also how sturdy it can be. You can pack a lot and stuff and stuff stuff in here and it's still not super heavy.
It comes with plenty of pockets and spots to fit things. Everything can have its own place. I love how easy it is to strap on and how the straps stay in place once you start wearing it.
This bag doesn't slide around on your back at all and I like that because with moving around a lot bags tend to slide around.
I like how easy it is to clean and store when not in use!!
review.name: Light but sturdy!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I love to go hiking so I was super excited to get this Speed Lite 30 bag by Deuter! The bag itself is well made, the quality is great! I am so impressed with just how lightweight this bag is! Even with all my gear in it, it is still so easy to carry. I can move so much more freely with this bag. Wearing the bag is super comfortable, the straps are nice and padded. The straps are easily adjustable to fit both my partner and I. The bag stays secure with the wrap around fins. With my old hiking gear, my back was always bothering by the time I was done my hike but with this bag, I have absolutely no discomfort. I love the pockets on the shoulder straps, it is super convenient to have my essentials easily accessible. The inside of the bag is large and also has more pockets. The bag offers plenty of space for all my hiking supplies. The fabric is made with 100% recycled materials. I love that this bag comes with a lifetime guarantee that if for any reason the bag is damaged, it will be fixed or replaced if needed. If you are a hiker, I highly recommend this bag! This would also make a fabulous gift!
review.name: High quality & lightweight

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The all new Speed Lite 30 bag is a must have for anyone who enjoys outdoors. Light weight and enough storage for your hiking trips. Easy to pack and pockets for everything you travel with. Use while in the woods on a camping excursion - or goin on a getaway out of town. Tough enough for anything you throw at it.
review.name: Versatile

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The Deuter Speed Lite 30 is the perfect pack for hiking.. long or short.  It is light weight and easy to carry. It is ventilated and lightly loaded for coolness and comfort. Multiple pockets allow you to quickly access items you need.
review.name: Carries all you need

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I was in need for the perfect hiking backpack and I found the most perfect one. review.reviewBody: I was looking for lightweight pack to use as a daypack.   The features I wanted were vest straps, a large pocket on the front, a place to store my trekking poles, and pockets on the straps and belt.  This pack checked all the boxes.  It is a comfortable, good looking pack.   I am not able to access and return my water bottle while wearing the pack which is not uncommon with smaller backpacks.   I solved that by adding an after-market pocket from Justin at Etsy to one of the shoulder straps.  The pocket that is on the left strap just fits my iPhone 16 Plus in an Otterbox case.

review.reviewBody: Great pack for ultra hikes. You barely notice you’re carrying one.

review.reviewBody:
I bought this to use on road and mountain bike adventures. It’s worked out perfectly so long as I don’t put the weight up high.
Very well made and much more visible than the black Patagonia bag it’s replacing. Highly.
review.name: Slim and well balanced

review.reviewBody: Traversed a few mountains and have been along the Pacific Coast with this pack and I can tell you, no issues with discomfort, plenty of space for my short treks. I've had several packs but this was my first Deuter. With a life long warranty to replace it no matter where and what it's been through its a no brainer for me.
review.name: Light weight, comfortable fitting

review.reviewBody: I bought this because I got a dog. Dog and I love to hike but my little Osprey pack was too small to hold my food and water and hers, plus extra gear and layers. So I upgraded to this 25L pack. Perfect! Also, I loved that it has a wide waste belt for comfort when hauling heavier stuff. Dueter is a great brand and I also have their larger 65+10 long haul pack. For my body, both are a great fit. Highly recommend this. Backcountry is great as always too.
review.name: Great pack

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The Speed Lite 25 is a great bag for day hiking or for a 1-night overnight adventure.    It is durable but at the same time is lightweight and provides comfortable padding.  It has a thoughtful design to store gear.    We love that there are several pockets on the shoulder straps and hip belt to store phone or snacks at the ready.  Also there are stretchable but secure spots on the side of the pack perfect for water bottles.
review.name: Great Pack For Day Hiking

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This was my first experience with Deuter and am impressed!  The 25-liter daypack is perfect for longer day treks as well as hiking with our family of 3.  There's plenty of storage including the large main compartment, hydration compartment which can also be used for additional storage, large front pouch, 2 large water bottle pockets (can hold my 32oz wide mouth), zippered belt pouch, 2 strap pockets (1 zippered), a zippered top pouch plus tons of gear loops.  It's easy to keep everything organized and accessible on our treks.  We're in an extremely hot environment and the pack breathes well, is well balanced and wears comfortably.  Construction-wise, it is well made and am impressed with their repair policy if ever needed. I'm super happy and looking forward to many adventures!
review.name: Excellent Daypack!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This backpack is awesome! It’s perfect for all your hiking needs. It’s lightweight and have multiple pockets for your key, water, hydro towels, shades and more. The straps are very well made and are padded for that extra stability.
review.name: Awesome bag!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I live in Utah which is HUGE for camping/hiking and outdoors I want to say. I used this backpack for a few hikes before I did my review to make sure I could review it properly. Great light backpack it’s very handy and had nice compartments and did not ever feel like it got caught up ln my shoulders etc I loved it but I would personally prefer a black pack with reflective on it but that’s just my style preference.
review.name: Great option for a hike or camping

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This lightweight but sturdy bag is perfect not only for hiking but for all your outdoor activity storage needs. I take it with me to the park with children to help store snacks, water, accessories, first aid etc. Perfect for long hikes through trails or mountains. The built in straps by the handle help you control how snug/tight you want it to be to the back of your shoulder blade, when loosened the back pad is made of extremely breathable material that keeps you cool. The shoulder straps have built in sleeve, zipper compartment, and eyeglass holder. The bag also had hip fins that can be adjusted and buckled to keep the bag in place with minimal movement as your body is moving. Would highly recommend this bag for any level hiker due to its lightweight nature and large capacity to hold everything you need for your next outdoor adventure.
review.name: Durable but lightweight outdoor bag

review.reviewBody:
Firstly, the chamois, the Motion Airgel. It's blue, has a more solid feel to it and is the most comfortable chamois I've ever had the pleasure to ride on. No more sitting on an oversize foam pad or a wet diaper. 
Second, the waistband. The flat elastic band was new to me and I like it. While I've found that it does fold over during rides, so does every other waistband I've ever worn, and this with no cord to further restrict, I find it a definite improvement.
Third, the inseam - it's long. It comes down to about an inch above my kneecap. Perfect for my rather thin thighs.
Fourth, everything else - is fine. Nice compressive fabric. The thin flexi grippers do their job invisibly.
I'd like to try some of those pricy Assos (etc) shorts sometime, but a can't imagine that they justify the upcharge from these shorts.

review.reviewBody: I use these for the yard and bad weather. They are perfect. Very comfortable to walk around in and one feels very safe and secure from mud, rain, insects, or whatever. I love the sunny happy color and design. Easy to get on and off as well! No tugging! Love them!

review.reviewBody: After at least ten years, I had to replace my old Bogs garden boots which I wear almost every day in the summer, and often in the winter. After that length of time, I finally wore a hole in them! So, on to these super cute and comfortable Bogs ankle boots. The best feature is that I can step right into them. Taking them off is easy, too. I wear a size 8 and that's what I bought. I felt they ran a tiny bit large, so I switched the insole to the fleece type which definitely fit me better.
review.name: Great garden boots

review.reviewBody: I bought these cute rain boots for my daughter and she loves them. ❤️ We live in the country and when it rains the ground gets really sloppy, but she wears them every time she goes outside to feed the dogs, gardening, mowing and so many other things because there is always something to do here. She said that they are light weight, comfortable, easy to slip off, protects from snakes and so very cute. We bought highly recommend buying them . I have also ordered her a pair of tall periwinkle boots. I am ordering her a pair of the "Rose Garden " low cut rain boots. You will love ❤️ these boots.
review.name: Great for country life

review.reviewBody: As expected, without option of half sizes, the BOGS boots did not work for me-- was too small, 7 was too big. Regretfully returned both sizes.
